---
import '../styles/global.css';
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base title="Patina | Andy Widjaja" description="Cognitive AI that learns your judgment over time. Observer/builder architecture with bounded autonomy.">
  <Header />

  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4 mb-8">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Patina</h1>
      <a
        href="https://github.com/Sanctum-Origo-Systems/patina"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="text-text-secondary hover:text-accent transition-colors font-mono text-sm"
      >
        repo &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Problem -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">Problem</h2>
      <p class="text-text-primary leading-relaxed">
        Every AI conversation starts from zero. The system forgets what you told it
        yesterday, repeats mistakes you already corrected, and never develops judgment
        about how <em>you</em> work. I built Patina because I wanted an AI that
        accumulates understanding: a persistent belief graph of user judgment that
        compounds over time instead of resetting.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Architecture -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">Architecture</h2>
      <div class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-md p-6 overflow-x-auto">
        <img src="/patina-arch-light.svg" alt="Patina architecture: observer, builder, human gate with self-improvement loop" class="w-full dark:hidden" />
        <img src="/patina-arch-dark.svg" alt="Patina architecture: observer, builder, human gate with self-improvement loop" class="w-full hidden dark:block" />
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Key Numbers -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">By the numbers</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
        <div class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-md p-4 text-center">
          <div class="text-xl font-semibold text-text-primary">31</div>
          <div class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary mt-1">MCP tools</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-md p-4 text-center">
          <div class="text-xl font-semibold text-text-primary">735</div>
          <div class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary mt-1">tests</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-md p-4 text-center">
          <div class="text-xl font-semibold text-text-primary">30</div>
          <div class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary mt-1">PRs merged</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-surface border border-border rounded-md p-4 text-center">
          <div class="text-xs font-mono text-success mt-1">running since</div>
          <div class="text-lg font-semibold text-text-primary">May 26</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Self-improvement thesis -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">Self-improvement thesis</h2>
      <p class="text-text-primary leading-relaxed">
        The interesting constraint: how do you let a system improve itself without
        losing control? Patina tracks which beliefs lead to good outcomes and which
        get corrected. It proposes changes to its own behavior through the same PR
        pipeline it uses for everything else, so no self-modification ships without
        human review. The system gets better, stays safe, and remains interpretable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Novel contribution -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-3">Novel contribution</h2>
      <p class="text-text-primary leading-relaxed">
        Most AI agents either do too much unsupervised or too little to be useful.
        Patina instantiates CAIS principles in a personal cognitive system: the observer
        and builder are separated by an air gap, the human merge gate bounds autonomy
        without crippling capability, and the self-improvement loop is governed, not
        open-ended. It's graduated autonomy as a running system, not a paper.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
